    "minutes": "MINUTES OF\nMUNICIPAL COUNCIL\nWORKSESSION MEETING\nOctober 20, 2025\n\nA Worksession Meeting of the Municipal Council of the Township of Edison was held in the Council Chambers of the Municipal Complex. The meeting was called to order at 6:02 p.m. by Council President Patel followed by the Pledge of Allegiance.\n\nPresent were Councilmembers Brescher, Coyle, Harris, Patil, Shmuel and Council President Patel.\n\nCouncilmember Dima was absent.\n\nAlso present were Township Clerk Russomanno, Deputy Clerk McCray, Township Attorney Rainone, Business Administrator Alves-Viveiros, CFO Vallejo, Police Chief [REVIEW: rank unclear - appears to be Chief], Fire Chief Toth and Cameraman Bhatty.\n\nThe Township Clerk advised that adequate notice of this meeting, as required by the Open Public Meetings Act of 1975, has been provided by an Annual Notice sent to The Home News Tribune, The Star Ledger, Desi Talk and News India Times on November 18, 2024 and posted in the Main Lobby of the Municipal Complex on the same date.\n\nThis meeting is available on the following link:\n\nhttps://cablecast.edisonnj.org/internetchannel/show/3919\n\n4.\tREVIEW OF MINUTES\n\n\tCombined meeting of October 8, 2025\tNo comments were made.\n\n5.\tPROPOSED ORDINANCES:\n\n\tORDINANCES 2261, 2262 AND 2263\n\n\tCouncil President Patel asked about the violation schedule in 2263 regarding the separation between under 18 and over 18. Councilmember Harris asked about confiscation provisions for juveniles versus adults. Police Chief explained these are electric scooters traveling at high speeds on highways, not e-bikes. The ordinance allows enforcement under Title 39 or local ordinance. For juveniles, parents would be issued the summons and the scooter would be impounded. The ordinance prohibits scooters on highways but allows them in neighborhoods. Councilmember Shmuel asked about state law. Chief explained the state limits motorized vehicles to 19mph and many towns are adopting similar ordinances for safety. Council President Patel provided written suggestions including lamp requirements, two-hand operation and prohibiting charging in right-of-ways. Councilmember Patil asked for clarification that this covers scooters not e-bikes. Chief confirmed e-bikes are legal and this ordinance addresses scooters, hoverboards, razors and similar motorized devices traveling on major roadways.\n\n6.\tFROM THE BUSINESS ADMINISTRATOR:\n\ta. through e.\tNo comments were made.\n\n7.\tFROM THE DEPARTMENT OF FINANCE:\n\ta. through d.\tNo comments were made.\n\n8.\tFROM THE DEPARTMENT OF PLANNING AND ENGINEERING:\n\n\tCouncilmember Shmuel asked about the timeline for the extension in item d. Ms. Alves-Viveiros explained approximately six months for the project. Council President Patel asked for details on items a and b to be provided by email regarding the letter of endorsement.\n\n9.\tFROM THE DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC WORKS:\n\ta. through i.\tNo comments were made.\n\n10.\tFROM THE DEPARTMENT OF RECREATION:\n\ta. and b.\tNo comments were made.\n\n11.\tFROM THE DEPARTMENT OF WATER AND SEWER:\n\n\ta.\tCouncilmember Brescher asked how many vendors for emergency water main system services. [REVIEW: response indicated three contractors - Fletcher Creamer, B&W Construction, and Waters & Bugbee]. Councilmember Harris asked about the cost of the recent water main break repair. Ms. Alves-Viveiros will provide estimate and explained this is the typical annual allocation for emergency services.\n\n12.\tFROM THE CHIEF OF POLICE:\n\n\ta.\tCouncil President Patel asked about monthly rent for the substation. Chief confirmed no rent. Councilmember Coyle asked about daily occupation. Chief explained the substation keeps officers on the road by allowing processing at the mall rather than headquarters and is used for reports and operations. Council President Patel noted it is a longstanding five-year agreement.\n\n13.\tFROM THE CHIEF OF FIRE:\n\ta.\tNo comments were made.\n\n14.\tORAL PETITIONS AND REMARKS:\n\n\tElizabeth Conway asked about the memo park substation and whether it will be used similarly to years ago. She asked about a Comcast contact person and requested updates on Inman Avenue intersections at Rahway, Tingley and Old Raritan. She asked about e-bike regulations and helmets. She urged the Council to move forward on the six minute speaking time. Ms. Alves-Viveiros directed her to email Council President Patel or Councilmember Coyle regarding Comcast and explained the administration is reviewing sight triangles at the Inman Avenue locations. Chief explained helmets are required for e-bikes and the administration is monitoring state regulations while prioritizing the e-scooter ordinance due to immediate safety concerns.\n\n\tJoyce [REVIEW: last name unclear] wished everyone happy Diwali and discussed the gallery display idea. She spoke about the six minute speaking time and Board of Education speaking time. She mentioned the Human Relations Committee and concerns about tree removal and flooding. She encouraged seniors to obtain legacy cards from the Board of Education office.\n\n\tAnthony DeAmorin requested the Council work with the county on a crosswalk at Woodbridge Avenue and the Greenway with lights and a crossing guard to promote bicycle traffic to Herbert Hoover School. He commended the Police Department for their success solving crimes and increased visibility.\n\n\t[REVIEW: speaker name - possibly remaining anonymous as stated] apologized for previous name-calling directed at councilmembers and requested restoration of public speaking time and rebuttal.\n\n\tHearing no further comments, this public hearing was closed, on a motion made by Councilmember Harris seconded by Councilmember Brescher, with all in favor.\n\n15.\tCOUNCIL COMMITTEES AND BOARD/COMMISSION LIAISON REPORTS:\n\n\tCouncilmember Brescher requested a summary from [REVIEW: staff member name unclear - sounds like \"Mr. Deal\"] regarding Veterans Park items and bid status for the following meeting. Councilmember Coyle announced scheduling a meeting with DPW regarding winter preparation.\n\n16.\tPOINTS OF LIGHT:\n\n\tCouncil President Patel wished everyone a happy and prosperous Diwali and asked Fire Chief Toth to speak about safety precautions. Chief Toth announced the fourth annual Diwali festival Saturday with 15,000 expected and stressed fireworks safety including using only legal fireworks sold in stores, being 18 years old, having water nearby and avoiding illegal aerial fireworks. Councilmember Coyle acknowledged the soft opening of the Edison Youth Sports Training Center, a 29,000 square foot facility built in 22 months for $12.5 million that will serve generations. Council President Patel announced early voting starts Saturday October 25th at [REVIEW: location unclear], trunk or treat Thursday October 30th from 4 to 8 p.m. at Papaianni Park and congratulated Councilmember [REVIEW: name unclear - sounds like \"Dave Minchillo\"] on his recent wedding.\n\n17.\tDISCUSSION ITEMS:\n\nCouncilmember Brescher:\na. None\n\nCouncilmember Coyle:\na. Commended the Water and Sewer Department for hiring and training Edison residents\n\nCouncilmember Harris:\na. None\n\nCouncilmember Patil:\na. Asked about Comcast rollout completion timeline and shared council calendar with Clerk to avoid scheduling conflicts with holidays\n\nCouncilmember Shmuel:\na. None\n\nCouncil Vice President [REVIEW: name - possibly Kentos based on earlier reference but marked absent in this meeting]:\na. None\n\nCouncil President Patel:\na. Asked about oversight of Red Roof Inn. Chief explained numerous law enforcement operations and ongoing issues with county and state placements. Township is working on an ordinance regarding state placements.\n\nOn a motion made by Councilmember Harris seconded by Councilmember Brescher with all in favor, the meeting was adjourned at 6:50pm.\n\n\n_______________________________    ____________________________________________\nNishith Patel                                          Cheryl Russomanno, RMC\nCouncil President                                      Municipal Clerk"
