    "minutes": "MINUTES OF\nMUNICIPAL COUNCIL\nWORKSESSION MEETING\nJanuary 12, 2026\n\nA Worksession Meeting of the Municipal Council of the Township of Edison was held in the Council Chambers of the Municipal Complex. The meeting was called to order at 6:04 p.m. by Council President Coyle followed by the Pledge of Allegiance.\n\nPresent were Councilmembers Brescher, Dima, Harris, Patil, Patel, Shmuel and Council President Coyle.\n\nAlso present were Township Clerk Russomanno, Deputy Clerk McCray, Township Attorney Rainone, Business Administrator Alves-Viveiros and Cameraman Bhatty.\n\nThe Township Clerk advised that adequate notice of this meeting, as required by the Open Public Meetings Act of 1975, has been provided by an Annual Notice sent to The Home News Tribune, The Star Ledger, Desi Talk and News India Times on November 17, 2025 and posted in the Main Lobby of the Municipal Complex on the same date.\n\nThis meeting is available on the following link:\n\nhttps://cablecast.edisonnj.org/internetchannel/show/3972\n\n4.\tPRESENTATION 250TH ANNIVERSARY OF OUR COUNTRY\n\nCouncil President Coyle read into the record:\n\nThis year, 2026, communities all across the country will be participating in America 250, a celebration of the 250th anniversary of the Declaration of Independence and the founding of the United States. Tonight, Edison will kick off America 250 Edison, a celebration of unity in Edison and pride in the United States. For months, this growing committee of Township employees, historic community leaders such as Walter Stossel and many others have together planned a series of events that recognize Edison's Revolutionary heritage. Events that Edison has traditionally done such as the Memorial Day Parade and the July 4th celebration will be enhanced to include America 250 celebrations and new events are being planned for all ages and all parts of the Township. As a lifelong resident of Edison, all of us are excited. Edison TV has been working hard creating a series of historic minutes that will be shown on TV this year. From the settlement of this area in 1666 to the Edison we know today, these minutes will tell our history in a visual way. Tonight we will premiere one of the minutes and a presentation by the Edison High School Drama Class of Life in Edison 1776.\n\nCouncil Vice President Harris gave a brief overview of the Rev 250 Committee function and events.\n\n5.\tFROM MAYOR SAM JOSHI:\n\ta. through m.\t\tNo comments were made.\n\n6.\tPROPOSED ORDINANCES:\n\nORDINANCE AMENDING ARTICLE V, \"BOARDS, COMMISSIONS, COMMITTEES AND AGENCIES,\" OF CHAPTER 2, \"ADMINISTRATION,\" OF THE MUNICIPAL CODE.\nNo comments were made.\n\nORDINANCE AMENDING CHAPTER 39, \"LAND USE,\" SECTION §39-12.15, \"TECHNICAL REVIEW COMMITTEE,\" OF THE CODE OF THE TOWNSHIP OF EDISON\n\nCouncilmember Patil asked because this won't be a public meeting, will those meeting minutes be documented and available on the website. Mr. Rainone explained the Technical Review Committee is really just a technical review of the application and once those notes are done that application will go to the Planning Board so yes, by that nature they would be publicly available. The purpose is to streamline the process.\n\n7.\tFROM THE BUSINESS ADMINISTRATOR:\n\ta. through u.\t\tCouncilmember Patil is happy to see many choices with many vendors in the professional service contracts listed.\n\n8.\tFROM THE DEPARTMENT OF FINANCE:\n\ta.\t\t\tNo comments were made.\n\n9.\tFROM THE DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH:\n\ta.\t\t\tNo comments were made.\n\n10.\tFROM THE DEPARTMENT OF PLANNING AND ENGINEERING:\n\ta.\t\t\tNo comments were made.\n\n11.\tFROM THE DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC WORKS:\n\ta.\t\t\tNo comments were made.\n\n12.\tORAL PETITIONS AND REMARKS:\n\nDr. Akhtar Nasser, Pleasant Avenue, passed out to all Councilmembers, Attorney and Administration a summary of questions, state statutes and ordinances regarding the Planning Board's December 15th approval of 1039 Amboy Avenue. He will meet with the Attorney after the meeting. The Attorney will review all his concerns.\n\nAnthony DeAmorin suggested, as a point of recommendation, the Council allow back and forth with the public.\n\n[REVIEW: third speaker name unclear from transcript — John or similar — played music during public comment]\n\nHearing no further comments, this public hearing was closed, on a motion made by Councilmember [REVIEW: mover name unclear], seconded by Councilmember [REVIEW: seconder name unclear], with all in favor.\n\n13.\tPOINTS OF LIGHT:\n\nCouncil President Coyle announced the following upcoming events. The Middlesex County Clerk's Association is sponsoring a blood drive on Thursday, January 15th in the Council Chambers from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. Monday, January 19th Township offices will be closed in observance of Martin Luther King's Birthday. The Dr. King Celebration and Service on January 20th at the Minue [REVIEW: location name unclear] will be open to the public 5 p.m. to 9 p.m.\n\n14.\tDISCUSSION ITEMS:\n\nCouncilmember Dima:\na. None\n\nCouncil Vice President Harris:\na. None\n\nCouncilmember Patel:\na. None\n\nCouncilmember Patil:\na. None\n\nCouncil President Coyle:\na. Thanked residents for attending and students for the 250th anniversary presentation\n\nOn a motion made by Councilmember [REVIEW: mover name unclear from transcript], seconded by Councilmember [REVIEW: seconder name unclear from transcript], with all in favor, the meeting was adjourned at 6:43pm.\n\n\n_______________________________\t\t\t____________________________________________\nJay Coyle\t\t\t\t\tCheryl Russomanno, RMC\nCouncil President\t\t\t\tMunicipal Clerk"
